Sassa accepts that it should have acted more quickly in approaching the Constitutional Court to disclose that it would be necessary to deviate from the time frames in the Nov 2015 progress reportIt finds itself in this position because it tried to find ways to implement, in an incremental way the plan announced in Nov 15 progress reportSassa s technical advisors confirmed it was not realistic to expect any competing supplier to offer to do what CPS has and can do for the interim period required for a competitive bidding processOf concern is that if SASSA fails to provide a network for cash payments approximately 40 percent of SASSA beneficiaries will not receive payments from April 1, 2007 because they don t have PINs but rely on biometric authentication to withdraw their money&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8211;Trengrove SC First priority is to ensure that all social grants are paid on time. It can only do so by contracting with CPS to continue paying the social grants for some time.Therefore would be appropriate for Treasury to allow SASSA to deviate provided it contracts with CPS for no longer than the time it reasonably requiresTrengrove considers two years to be too longSocial Development says it believes that the current R16.44 per beneficiary per month cost will be maintainedIf the implementation of the interim contract will result in SASSA s budget allocation of about R2.258bn be exceeded Treasury s written approval will be sought.&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;-Draft order That the agreement with CPS must be made public That the PP and AG or other such institutions must jointly monitor the terms and conditions of the interim contract &#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;Answers to ConCourtWho was the person responsible for determining on behalf of SASSA whether SASSA itself would not be able to pay the grants by the end of March 2017? Answer: The person was the CEO (three different) on advice of Ms Mvulan. Mvulane was responsible for the management of the project in the Nov 15 progress report. ((This seems to point at a problem with staff changeover being problematic in the implementation))2. The date when the responsible person on behalf of SASSA first became aware that it would not be able to pay the grants itself by the end of March &#8211; April 19, 2016: The agency then sought an opinion from counsel on legal implications for SASA. On June 10 the legal opinion from Cassim SC and Mostert was sent to acting CEO Ms Ramokgopa.3. The exact dates when the responsible person on behalf of SASSA became aware that the respective time frames set out in paragraph 13 of its progress report to the court could not be fulfilled. &#8211; Unable to answer this question but suggests that this could be mid-April, but need further consultations to respond to this fully4. The reasons why this court was not immediately informed of this fact and who made the decision that it was not necessary to do so &#8211; No one made the decision not to inform this court, but accept that this court ought to have been informed at a much earlier state5. Whether the Minister was informed that SASSA would not be able to pay the grants by itself at the end of March 2017 and, if so when this happened &#8211; Yes, In October 2016 &#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;SASSA has not entered into an agreement with CPS The agreement is not yet negotiated and concluded 2. To the question on whether it was SASSA s contention that this agreement is lawful and in compliance with the procurement requirements of the Constitution and legislation . If the National Treasury approves the deviation for any resulting interim contract, the contract will comply with the applicable legislation.3. SASSA says it will provide the Court with a full road map on way forward, will continue with process of expert evaluation4. They do not have any problem with independent monitoring of SASSA and the payment of grants-Tna Reporter